ly the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William HEMPSTEAD was born about 1230, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son with Christina De Suffield."},"et":{"Abt 1230–":"umbes 1230–Surnud","1232–Female":"1232–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","Abt 1230":"umbes 1230","1232":"1232","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","Hempstede, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1230–":"noin 1230–Kuollut","1232–Female":"1232–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","Abt 1230":"noin 1230","1232":"1232","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","Hempstede, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England"},"fr":{"Abt 1230–":"environ 1230–Décédé","1232–Female":"1232–Décédée","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1230–Male":"1230–Décédé","Abt 1230":"environ 1230","1232":"1232","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","Hempstede, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William HEMPSTEAD est né environ 1230, à Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Christina De Suffield."},"de":{"Abt 1230–":"um 1230–Verstorben","1232–Female":"1232–Verstorben","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","1230–Male":"1230–Verstorben","Abt 1230":"um 1230","1232":"1232","1230":"1230","1250":"1250","Hempstede, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingd